Volume 45, Issue 2

SIAM Rev., 45(2), 167–256. (90 pages)

The Structure and Function of Complex Networks

Related Databases

Web of Science

You must be logged in with an active subscription to view this.

Article Data

History

Published online: 04 August 2006

Keywords

networks, graph theory, complex systems, computer networks, social networks, random graphs, percolation theory

AMS Subject Headings

05C75, 05C90, 94C15

Publication Data

ISSN (print): 0036-1445
ISSN (online): 1095-7200
Publisher: Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics
CODEN: siread
M. E. J. Newman
https://doi.org/10.1137/S003614450342480

Inspired by empirical studies of networked systems such as the Internet, social networks, and biological networks, researchers have in recent years developed a variety of techniques and models to help us understand or predict the behavior of these systems. Here we review developments in this field, including such concepts as the small-world effect, degree distributions, clustering, network correlations, random graph models, models of network growth and preferential attachment, and dynamical processes taking place on networks.

Copyright © 2003 Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics
Permalink: https://doi.org/10.1137/S003614450342480
